      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix: treat trusted-proxy gateway auth as doctor auth proof",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- Count a complete `trusted-proxy` gateway setup as authentication proof for the network-exposure doctor check.\n- Keep incomplete trusted-proxy setups on the existing critical path by requiring both `gateway.auth.trustedProxy.userHeader` and `gateway.trustedProxies`.\n- Keep startup-invalid trusted-proxy/token conflicts and unsafe proxy source configs on specific critical paths.\n- Require every non-empty `gateway.trustedProxies` entry to be a host-scoped trusted proxy source before doctor downgrades exposed Gateway auth from critical to warning.\n- Replace the misleading token/`doctor --fix` remediation with trusted-proxy-specific proxy/firewall guidance.\n\n## Why\n\n`trusted-proxy` is an explicit gateway auth mode, and the gateway runtime already treats the proxy source boundary as security-sensitive. The doctor exposure check only recognized token/password shared-secret modes, so a LAN-bound trusted-proxy deployment could be reported as \"without authentication\" and nudged toward token repair even though the intended auth boundary is the reverse proxy.\n\nThis keeps the exposure warning, because a LAN-bound gateway still deserves review, but it no longer labels a complete trusted-proxy setup as unauthenticated.\n\nIt also avoids treating unsafe or startup-invalid trusted-proxy configs as proof: shared-token conflicts, missing user headers, missing proxy sources, broad proxy CIDRs/default routes, mixed exact-plus-broad proxy lists, and loopback proxy entries without explicit `allowLoopback` remain critical.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- Behavior addressed: LAN-bound Gateway configs using fully configured `trusted-proxy` auth were reported as unauthenticated by doctor/security.\n- Real environment tested: A real local OpenClaw config using `gateway.bind=lan`, `gateway.auth.mode=trusted-proxy`, and configured trusted proxies.\n- Exact steps or command run after this patch: `npm_config_cache=/private/tmp/openclaw-npm-cache npm exec --yes pnpm@11.2.2 -- node scripts/run-node.mjs doctor --lint --json`\n- Evidence after fix: Copied live output from the patched dev CLI included these `core/doctor/security` findings:\n\n```json\n[\n  {\n    \"checkId\": \"core/doctor/security\",\n    \"severity\": \"warning\",\n    \"message\": \"WARNING: Gateway bound to \\\"lan\\\" (0.0.0.0) with trusted-proxy authentication.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"checkId\": \"core/doctor/security\",\n    \"severity\": \"warning\",\n    \"message\": \"Ensure only configured trusted proxies can reach the Gateway port; block direct clients at a host firewall, network firewall, or loopback bind.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"checkId\": \"core/doctor/security\",\n    \"severity\": \"warning\",\n    \"message\": \"Docs: https://docs.openclaw.ai/gateway/trusted-proxy-auth\"\n  }\n]\n```\n\n- Observed result after fix: The trusted-proxy Gateway config is no longer reported as `CRITICAL` or \"without authentication\"; doctor keeps a network-exposure warning with trusted-proxy-specific guidance.\n- What was not tested: I did not test a live remote reverse-proxy login flow from this branch; the proof is limited to the doctor/security classification and remediation text.\n\n## Verification\n\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/commands/doctor-security.test.ts` - 40 tests passed\n- `./node_modules/.bin/oxfmt --check --threads=1 src/commands/doctor-security.ts src/commands/doctor-security.test.ts`\n- `git diff --check`\n- `npm_config_cache=/private/tmp/openclaw-npm-cache npm exec --yes pnpm@11.2.2 -- lint`\n",
        "branch": "fix-doctor-trusted-proxy-auth",
        "head_sha": "323929cb1b14b8718563ebff08d0427d1e277df9",
